<DOC><DOCNO> AP890224-0068 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 0557EST</FILEID><FIRST>u i PM-Bush-Boots     02-24 0229</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Bush-Boots,210</SECOND><HEAD>Bush Taking Cowboy Boots as Gifts for Chinese Leaders</HEAD><HEAD>With PM-Bush Rdp Bjt</HEAD><DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   President Bush, a self-proclaimed Texan, is takinghandmade, black leather cowboy boots to Beijing as gifts for China'stop leaders.   Moreover, Bush will throw a Texas-style barbecue in Beijing onSunday night in return for a banquet his Chinese hosts are giving inhis honor Saturday night in the Great Hall of the People.   In two days of meetings in the Chinese capital, Bush will conferwith 84-year-old Deng Xiaoping, the country's senior leader, as wellas President Yang Shangkun, Communist Party General Secretary ZhaoZiyang and Premier Li Peng.   Mrs. Bush's press secretary, Anna Perez, said the president hadthe boots made for the four Chinese leaders by R.J. Boot Co. ofHouston.   An American flag is emblazoned on the right boot and the Chineseflag on the left boot of each pair, she said. Ms. Perez said she didnot know how the bootmaker determined the leaders' shoe sizes.   The president's Sunday night banquet will feature barbecued beef,chicken, sausage and baked beans. Ms. Perez said Bush also wants toimport a popular Texas beer, Lone Star, for the occasion.   Bush also is carrying a gift of a golf putter for South KoreanPresident Roh Tae-woo. Bush will visit Seoul briefly Monday on hisway back to Washington.</TEXT></DOC>